name: Singleton Park Orchard
short_description: Heritage fruit in Swansea's largest park.
description: The Botanical Gardens and surrounding parkland contain variety of apple and pear trees open to the public.

name: Mumbles Coast Seaweed
description: The rocky shore at low tide near Mumbles Head is excellent for gathering traditional Welsh Laver seaweed.

name: Incredible Edible Swansea - Environment Centre
description: Public planters outside the Environment Centre featuring herbs, salad leaves, and seasonal vegetables.

name: Bishopston Valley Wild Garlic
description: The limestone valley floor is covered in wild garlic during the spring months.

name: Kilvey Hill Hazelnuts
short_description: Wild nuts with a city view.
description: The wooded slopes of Kilvey Hill offer plenty of hazel trees for nut gathering in the autumn.

name: Oxwich Bay Sea Kale
description: Wild Sea Kale can be found growing in the shingle and sand dunes at the back of the beach.

name: Cwmdonkin Park Blackberries
short_description: Urban brambles in Dylan Thomas' park.
description: Wild blackberries grow along the perimeter fences and upper wooded edges of the park.

name: Penllergare Valley Woods Sweet Chestnuts
description: Mature sweet chestnut trees are found in the mixed woodland areas of this restored estate.

name: Victoria Park Herb Bed
description: Small community-managed herb garden near the park entrance featuring kitchen staples.

name: Swansea Canal Elder
description: Numerous elder trees grow along the canal path between Clydach and Pontardawe.

name: Clyne Gardens Sloes
description: Blackthorn bushes (sloes) can be found in the wilder scrubby sections of the gardens.

name: Rhossili Cliff Samphire
description: Gather rock samphire from the lower cliff faces near the Causeway (take care with tides).

name: Underhill Park Orchard
description: A small number of community-access apple trees located near the sports fields.

name: Brynmill Park Rosehips
description: Wild rose bushes found in the park shrubbery borders provide rosehips in late autumn.

name: Gower Coast Path Gorse
description: Edible gorse flowers can be found along almost the entire length of the coastal path.
